        <h1>The Future of Responsive Web Design</h1>
        <p class="article-meta">By Rayan Fiver • 15 Apr 2026 • 8 min read</p>
        <p class="article-intro">
          Responsive web design has evolved significantly. Discover modern approaches including container queries, flexible grids, and adaptive images that create truly fluid experiences across all devices.
        </p>
      </header>

      <article class="article-content">
        <h2>Evolution of Responsive Design</h2>
        <p>
          When Ethan Marcotte introduced responsive web design in 2010, it revolutionized how we build for the web. Today, responsive design is no longer optional—it's essential. With over 60% of web traffic coming from mobile devices, designing for responsiveness from the start is non-negotiable.
        </p>

        <h2>Mobile-First Approach</h2>
        <p>
          The mobile-first strategy means starting your design for small screens, then progressively enhancing for larger viewports. This approach ensures your site works everywhere and helps prioritize essential content.
        </p>

        <div class="code-block">
          <div class="code-header">
            <span>mobile-first-example.css</span>
            <button class="copy-btn" type="button">Copy</button>
          </div>
          <pre><code><span class="token-comment\">/* Mobile first - base styles */</span>
.container {
  width: 100%;
  padding: 0 16px;
}

<span class=\"token-comment\">/* Tablet and up */</span>
@media (min-width: 768px) {
  .container {
    width: 750px;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }
}

<span class=\"token-comment\">/* Desktop */</span>
@media (min-width: 1024px) {
  .container {
    width: 960px;
  }
}</code></pre>
        </div>

        <h2>Modern CSS Features</h2>
        <p>
          CSS Grid, Flexbox, and Container Queries have transformed how we create layouts. These tools make it easier than ever to build truly responsive interfaces without relying on complex media queries or JavaScript.
        </p>

        <h3>Key Modern Features</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>CSS Grid:</strong> Two-dimensional layouts with automatic wrapping</li>
          <li><strong>Flexbox:</strong> One-dimensional layouts with powerful alignment options</li>
          <li><strong>Container Queries:</strong> Responsive components independent of viewport</li>
          <li><strong>CSS Custom Properties:</strong> Dynamic theming and responsive values</li>
          <li><strong>Aspect Ratio:</strong> Maintain proportions without padding hacks</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Fluid Typography</h2>
        <p>
          Instead of changing font sizes at specific breakpoints, fluid typography scales smoothly from small to large viewports. This creates a more refined reading experience across all devices.
        </p>

        <div class="code-block">
          <div class=\"code-header\">
            <span>fluid-typography.css</span>
            <button class=\"copy-btn\" type=\"button\">Copy</button>
          </div>
          <pre><code><span class=\"token-comment\">/* Fluid typography that scales smoothly */</span>
h1 {
  font-size: clamp(1.5rem, 4vw, 3rem);
}

p {
  font-size: clamp(1rem, 2vw, 1.2rem);
}</code></pre>
        </div>

        <h2>Performance Considerations</h2>
        <p>
          Responsive design must also consider performance. Optimize images, minimize CSS, and use modern image formats like WebP. Tools like Lighthouse help identify performance bottlenecks and opportunities for improvement.
        </p>

        <h2>Accessibility in Responsive Design</h2>
        <p>
          Responsive design must include accessibility from the start. Ensure touch targets are at least 44x44 pixels, text has sufficient contrast, and keyboard navigation works flawlessly across all screen sizes.
        </p>

        <h2>Key Takeaways</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Mobile-first design ensures better experiences for all users</li>
          <li>Modern CSS makes responsive design more straightforward</li>
          <li>Fluid typography improves readability across devices</li>
          <li>Performance and accessibility are integral to responsive design</li>
          <li>Test on real devices, not just browser emulation</li>
        </ul>
      </article>

